 to the initial evidence of erosion in their country's industrial, financial, naval, and military power. The British example suggests that statesmen may be slow to recognize shifts in international position, in part because they rely heavily on simple but often distorting indicators of relative capabilities. In a new afterword, Friedberg examines current debates about whether America is in decline, arguing that American power will remain robust for some time to come.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aAsquith, Herbert.  aAustria-Hungary.  aCape Colony.  aChamberlain, Joseph.  aCrimean War.  aCustoms Board.  aDilke, Charles.  aFashoda crisis.  aGiffen, Robert.  aGreat Depression.  aHamilton, Edward.  aKabul-Kandahar line.  aKriegspiel.  aKruger telegram incident.  aLiberal Unionist party.  aLiberal party.  aMullaly, Colonel.  aNapoleonic wars.  aNational Fair Trade League.  aNewfoundland.  aPeel, Sir Robert.  aalcohol, taxes on.  aarms race models.  abalance-of-power theory.  abattleships.  abelief systems.  abudget cycles.  abudget.  acalculative model.  acamels.  aconscription.  acost of living.  acustoms duties.  adiplomacy.  adumping.  aeconomic development.  aeconomic growth.  aeducation.  aexpenditures.  afree trade.  afree-trade areas.  agigantism.  agovernment.  ahegemonic stability theory.  aimperialism.  aimports.  airon production.  amathematical realism.  aneorealism.  aperceptual model.  aproduction.  aprotectionism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400836406zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978140